  "opinion": "As an 82-year-old woman living in Milan, I've seen many changes in the world, and social media is one of the biggest. I use it a few times a week to stay connected with family and friends, especially since I'm an immigrant and my loved ones are far away. Dealing with fake content on these platforms is something I've learned to handle through my own experiences and simple habits. First, I always take my time when I see something surprising or shocking online. My high openness means I'm curious about new things, but my low conscientiousness reminds me not to rush into sharing or believing everything I read. I check the source by looking at who posted it and if it's from a trusted person or organization. For example, if I see a news story about health, I might ask my doctor or look it up on reliable websites I know from my gardening and knitting communities, where people share accurate tips. I also rely on my real-life connections; I often call my friends or family to discuss what I've seen, which helps me sort out truth from fiction. My moderate extraversion means I enjoy these conversations, and my low agreeableness makes me comfortable questioning things without worrying about offending others. Since I'm self-employed as a delivery driver, I've met many people in Milan, and I've learned that not everyone has good intentions, so I'm cautious. I don't spend too much time on social media, which helps me avoid getting overwhelmed by fake content. Instead, I focus on my hobbies like hiking and gardening, which keep me grounded in reality. My Islamic faith teaches me to seek truth and avoid spreading lies, so I make sure not to share anything unless I'm sure it's correct. In short, managing fake content is about being patient, checking facts, and trusting the people and values I know from my long life.",
